\begin_layout Subsection
Results for PCA1 with patches
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Instead of computing a PCA components localized in a single pixel, we also
 tried by learning PCAs on patches of different sizes at each 
\emph on
j
\emph default
.
 This was motivated by a previous approach on audio (ESC50 dataset), where
 the size of the patches made a difference.
 We tried with 2x2, 4x2 and 4x4 patches and this performed well on subsets
 (10k images), increasing the performance.
 Nonetheless, the best result on whole CIFAR10 is 72% with 4x2 patches.
 Also, we had these results using a 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon-ratio=0.001$
\end_inset

 and we never tried without thresholding because there is a problem in:
 with 50k samples it exceeds memory limits (this can easily fix this by
 batch-projecting).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Other results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Effect of log: log features usually decrease the performance with PCA1.
 We applied the 
\begin_inset Formula $log(eps+features)$
\end_inset

 at the end of the pipeline, but before the final standardization for SVM.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Reversing PCA and modulus operator in PCA1: also following previous experiments
 in audio, we tried to reverse the application of PCA and modulus (namely,
 learning PCA on real values).
 It doesn’t change the results significantly.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Smoothing filter on PCA2: the feature vectors of PCA2 are bigger than the
 one of PCA1 because the subsampling happens 1 time less.
 We tried therefore to apply a 
\emph on
phi
\emph default
 smoothing on the vector after the PCA loop, but performance decreased.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Removing first order in PCA1: we tried to use only second order coefficients
 for PCA1 instead of the joint vector of order 1 and 2.
 This didn’t affect the performance, indicating that second order seems
 to be enough to represent the data.
 
